<think><details><summary>Thought Process</summary>
**Addressing the Bug's Demise**

It's gone! The `[baseline-browser-mapping]` error vanished. After a bit of detective work, I pinpointed an outdated `browserslist` dependency bundled within `next@16.0.4`. Updating to the most recent version of `next` seems to have done the trick and now it's resolved.


**Verifying Further Issues**

The `/profile` route's "Dynamic server usage" message is inconsequential, so I'm ignoring it for now. I've also examined the user's provided `@bash (20 8-225)` information, and focused on error lines 218-219. The root cause for the `baseline-browser-mapping` error was the outdated bundled `browserslist`. I will inform the user of these findings, and the changes I implemented to resolve this.


</details></think>

---

The warning `[baseline-browser-mapping] The data in this module is over two months old` was persisting because Next.js bundles its own version of `browserslist` (which includes this check), and the version in `next@16.0.4` was outdated despite your local `baseline-browser-mapping` being up to date.

I have updated `next` and `eslint-config-next` to the latest version (`16.0.6`), which includes the updated data (published Nov 28, 2025). The build now runs without these warnings.

Updated packages:
- `next`: `16.0.4` ‚Üí `^16.0.6`
- `eslint-config-next`: `16.0.4` ‚Üí `^16.0.6`
- `baseline-browser-mapping`: updated to latest (`2.8.32`)

Verified with `npm run build`, and the error is gone.
